<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 499px 269px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">Strategic Purpose</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p class="p1" data-pasted="true">Before defining structured AIR, it’s important to pause and ask:</p>
<p><strong>“Why are we collecting this information in the first place?”</strong></p>
<p>To avoid information overload and ensure data is actually useful, the standard recommends:</p>
<ul>
<li><span style="white-space: normal;"><span style="white-space:pre;">&nbsp;</span>Defining information requirements based on specific decisions or actions</span></li>
<li><span style="white-space: normal;">Ensuring information supports real operational or asset management needs</span></li>
<li><span style="white-space: normal;">Keeping information proportionate to its intended use</span></li>
</ul>
<p data-pasted="true">This process should begin by reviewing your Organizational Information Requirements (OIR), the long-term goals, responsibilities, and performance outcomes your organization is aiming to achieve.</p>
<p>AIR should directly support these goals by specifying the information needed to operate, maintain, and optimize key assets.</p>
<p>The following questions help you connect your organizational goals with specific asset data needs.</p>
<table style="width: 50%; margin: auto; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid; height: 409px;">
